<!-- ============= Introduction ====================================== -->
  <sect1 id="gparted-live-introduction">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <para>
    &livename; is a small bootable GNU/Linux distribution for x86
    based computers.  &livename; enables you to use all the <ulink
    type="http" url="http://gparted.org/features.php">features</ulink>
    of the latest versions of the <application>&appname;</application>
    application.
    </para>
    <para>
    This manual describes how to use the &livename; image, from boot up
    to shut down.
    </para>
  </sect1>
  
<!-- ============= Booting GParted Live ============================== -->
  <sect1 id="gparted-live-booting-gparted-live">
    <title>Booting GParted Live</title>
    <para>
    This section describes how to boot up &livename; on your computer.
    </para>
    <para>
    If your computer does not boot from CD-ROM discs or USB flash
    drives, then see <xref linkend="gparted-live-preparing-bios"/>.
    </para>
    <tip>
      <para>
      To learn how to write the &livename; image to removable media,
      such as CD-ROM or a USB flash drive, see
      <ulink type="http" url="http://gparted.org/livecd.php"/>.
      </para>
    </tip>

<!-- ============= Booting from Removable Media ====================== -->
    <sect2 id="gparted-live-booting-from-removable-media">
      <title>Booting from CD-ROM or USB Flash Drive</title>
      <para>
      To start &livename;:
        <orderedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Power on your computer with the media containing &livename;.
            </para>
            <itemizedlist>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                If you are using a USB flash drive, then insert the
                flash drive into an open USB port and turn on the
                power for your computer.
                </para>
              </listitem>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                If you are using a CD-ROM disc, then turn on the power
                for your computer and quickly insert the CD-ROM disc in
                the CD-ROM tray of your computer.
                </para>
              </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            To use the default settings, press the
            <keycap>Enter</keycap> key when the &livename; boot screen
            is displayed.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-boot-screen">
              <title>&livename; Boot Screen</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-boot-screen.jpeg">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-boot-screen.jpeg"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="JPEG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows &livename; boot screen.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
            <tip>
              <para>
              To use a different mode of &livename;, use the
              <keycap>Up arrow</keycap> key or <keycap>Down
              arrow</keycap> key to select the mode.  Press the
              <keycap>Enter</keycap> key to activate the mode.
              </para>
              <para>
              For example, to be able to use your CD-ROM R/W tray
              after booting &livename; select the
              <menuchoice><guimenu>Other modes of
              &livename;</guimenu></menuchoice> entry, and then select
              the <menuchoice><guimenu>To RAM</guimenu></menuchoice>
              entry.
              </para>
              <para>
              To return to the default &livename; boot screen, press
              the <keycap>Escape</keycap> key.
              </para>
              <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
              <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                   width of 510 pixels.
                   http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
              -->
              <figure id="gparted-live-boot-screen-other-modes">
                <title>Other modes of &livename;</title>
                <ulink type="http"
                       url="figures/gparted-live-boot-screen-other-modes.jpeg">
                  <inlinemediaobject>
                    <imageobject>
                      <imagedata 
                        fileref="figures/gparted-live-boot-screen-other-modes.jpeg"
                        width="510px" scalefit="1"
                        format="JPEG"/>
                      </imageobject>
                    <textobject>
                      <phrase>
                      Shows Other modes of &livename; screen.
                      </phrase>
                    </textobject>
                  </inlinemediaobject>
                </ulink>
              </figure>
            </tip>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            To use the standard US keymap, press the
            <keycap>Enter</keycap> key.
            </para>
            <para>
            If you require a different keymap then use the <keycap>Up
            arrow</keycap>, <keycap>Down arrow</keycap>, and
            <keycap>Enter</keycap> keys to choose an appropriate
            keymap for your keyboard.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-bootup-keymap-question">
              <title>Keymap Question</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-bootup-keymap-question.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-bootup-keymap-question.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows screen with keymap question prompt.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            To use the US English language, press the
            <keycap>Enter</keycap> key.
            </para>
            <para>
            If you desire a different language then type the number
            shown beside the langauge and press the
            <keycap>Enter</keycap> key.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-bootup-language-question">
              <title>Language Question</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-bootup-language-question.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-bootup-language-question.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows screen with language question prompt.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            To start up the default graphical environment and
            begin using the <application>&appname;</application>
            application, press the <keycap>Enter</keycap> key.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-bootup-video-mode-question">
              <title>Video Mode Question</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-bootup-video-mode-question.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-bootup-video-mode-question.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows screen with video mode prompt.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            You can now begin using the
            <application>&appname;</application> application.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-after-bootup">
              <title>Graphical Desktop with &appname;</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-after-bootup.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-after-bootup.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows screen with &appname; on a graphical desktop.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
            <note>
              <para>
              If your computer is unable to display the default
              graphical environment, then see <xref
              linkend="gparted-live-tips-on-booting-gparted-live"/>.
              </para>
            </note>
          </listitem>
        </orderedlist>
      </para>
    </sect2>

  </sect1>

<!-- ============= Using GParted Live ================================ -->
  <sect1 id="gparted-live-using-gparted-live">
    <title>Using &livename;</title>
    <para>
    This section describes how to use some of the features of
    &livename;.
    </para>

<!-- ============= Using GParted Application ========================= -->
    <sect2 id="gparted-live-using-gparted-application">

      <title>Using &appname; Application</title>
      <para>
      For instruction on how to use the
      <application>&appname;</application> application, please refer
      to the &appname; Application Help Manual.
      </para>
      <para>
      The &appname; Manual is available on the documentation page of
      the &appname; web site.  See <ulink type="http"
      url="http://gparted.org/documentation.php"/>.
      </para>
    </sect2>

<!-- ============= Enabling Network Access =========================== -->
    <sect2 id="gparted-live-enabling-network-access">

      <title>Enabling Network Access</title>
      <para>
      To enable wired ethernet TCP/IP networking on your computer:
        <orderedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Double-click the <guibutton>Terminal</guibutton> icon in
            the upper left hand side of the desktop.  This will open a
            terminal window.
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            At the terminal prompt enter the following command:
            <screen><prompt>user@debian:~$ </prompt><command>sudo dhclient eth0</command></screen>
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-enable-networking">
              <title>Terminal Window and Command to Enable Networking</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-enable-networking.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-enable-networking.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows terminal window with command to enable networking.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
            <para>
            Wired ethernet TCP/IP networking should now be enabled.
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Close the terminal window by entering the following
            command at the terminal prompt:
            <screen><prompt>user@debian:~$ </prompt><command>exit</command></screen>
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </orderedlist>
      </para>
    </sect2>

  </sect1>

<!-- ============= Finishing GParted Live Session ==================== -->
  <sect1 id="gparted-live-finishing-gparted-live-session">
    <title>Finishing &livename; Session</title>
    <para>
    This section describes how to finish your &livename; session.
    </para>

<!-- ============= Shutting Down GParted Live ======================== -->
    <sect2 id="gparted-live-shutting-down-gparted-live">
      <title>Shutting Down &livename;</title>
      <para>
      To shut down &livename;:
        <orderedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Double-click the <guibutton>Exit</guibutton> icon in
            the upper left hand side of the desktop.
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Select the
            <menuchoice><guimenu>Shutdown</guimenu></menuchoice> entry
            and click <guibutton>OK</guibutton>.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-shutdown-prompt">
              <title>Shutdown Prompt</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-shutdown-prompt.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-shutdown-prompt.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows window with shutdown prompt.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            When prompted, remove the CD-ROM disc or USB flash drive
            and press the <keycap>Enter</keycap> key.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-shutdown-remove-disc-prompt">
              <title>Remove Disc Prompt</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-shutdown-remove-disc-prompt.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-shutdown-remove-disc-prompt.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows screen with remove disc prompt.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Your computer will shut down.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </orderedlist>
      </para>
    </sect2>

  </sect1>

<!-- ============= Appendix A - Preparing BIOS ======================= -->
  <sect1 id="gparted-live-preparing-bios">
    <title>Appendix A: Preparing BIOS</title>
    <para>
    To boot the &livename; image from USB flash drive or CD-ROM disc,
    your computer BIOS must be properly configured.  More specifically
    the BIOS must be set to boot from CD-ROM and other removable
    devices before booting from hard disk drives.
    </para>

<!-- ============= Entering BIOS Setup =============================== -->
    <sect2 id="gparted-live-entering-bios-setup">

      <title>Entering BIOS Setup</title>
      <para>
      To enter the BIOS setup screen on you computer:
        <orderedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Turn on the power for your computer.
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Watch for a screen indicating which key to press to enter
            the BIOS setup screen.
            </para>
            <para>
            For example at the bottom of the following screen shot,
            the <keycap>F2</keycap> is used to enter the BIOS setup
            screen.  On other computers it might be the
            <keycap>Delete</keycap> key, the <keycap>Insert</keycap>
            key, the <keycap>F9</keycap> key, or some other key.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-bios-setup-prompt">
              <title>BIOS Setup Prompt</title>
              <ulink type="http"
                     url="figures/gparted-live-bios-setup-prompt.png">
                <inlinemediaobject>
                  <imageobject>
                    <imagedata 
                      fileref="figures/gparted-live-bios-setup-prompt.png"
                      width="510px" scalefit="1"
                      format="PNG"/>
                    </imageobject>
                  <textobject>
                    <phrase>
                    Shows screen with prompt to enter BIOS setup.
                    </phrase>
                  </textobject>
                </inlinemediaobject>
              </ulink>
            </figure>
            <note>
              <para>
              If you do not see a screen that indicates the key to
              press to enter BIOS setup, then you might need to
              consult the documentation that came with your computer.
              </para>
            </note>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Press and hold the appropriate key, noted from above, to
            enter BIOS setup.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </orderedlist>
      </para>
    </sect2>

<!-- ============= Setting BIOS Boot Order =========================== -->
    <sect2 id="gparted-live-setting-bios-boot-order">
      <title>Setting Boot Order in BIOS</title>
      <para>
        <orderedlist>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Read the BIOS setup screen instructions to learn how to
            navigate the menu options and how to change settings.
            </para>
          </listitem>
          <listitem>
            <para>
            Change the BIOS boot order so that CD-ROM and removable
            devices, such as a USB flash drive, are earlier in the
            boot order than hard disk drives.
            </para>
            <!-- ==== Figure ==== -->
            <!-- The GNOME Documentation Project recommends a maximum image
                 width of 510 pixels.
                 http://library.gnome.org/devel/gdp-style-guide/stable/screenshot-4.html.en
            -->
            <figure id="gparted-live-bios-setup-boot-order">
